File Permissions – The Basics

If you share a machine with other users, you probably don’t want them digging around your personal files (anyone else keep a digital diary?). Or maybe you have a server on which different groups of users will need to share files, but you need to ensure that the right boundaries exist — you don’t want members of one group accessing or modifying data that doesn’t belong to them.

File permissions control who can access files and what they are able to do with said files. Today, we’re going to cover the basics of file permissions in Linux, which inherited its permission scheme from Unix. (macOS is also a Unix-based OS, so much of what we’ll cover today is applicable to macOS as well).

Unix-style permissions are broken into three categories:

  • Owner
    • Permission given to a particular file or directory Owner — by default, the creator of said file/directory.
  • Group
    • Permission given to members of a particular Group — by default, the members of the creator’s primary group.
  • Others*
    • Others permissions apply to anyone logged in to the system.

*Note: You may also hear “Others” referred to as “World.”

In Ubuntu, you can examine the permissions for a given file or directory by opening Files, right-clicking the file or directory you wish you examine, selecting “Properties” from the menu, then selecting the “Permissions” tab in the Properties window:

In the screenshot above, we can see that the Owner (me) has read-write access to the diary, the Group (the jsilvey group, whose membership consists solely of my jsilvey account) has read-write access, and all Others have read-only access.

“Wait a second,” you may be thinking. “All Others have read access to the diary? Doesn’t that kind of, you know, defeat the point?”

So it would seem! But in truth, Others would not be able to read my secret diary unless they had access to the entire directory tree (/home/jsilvey/Documents) in which my file is located.

Let’s look at the permissions for the parent directory of “Documents,” which is my home directory (/home/jsilvey):

My user account and primary group have read-write access to /home/jsilvey, but Others have no permission at all. Even if Documents allowed Others read-write access, Others would not be able to read my file unless they had at least read access to the parent directory, /home/jsilvey.

Terminal — Or, what the heck is drwxr-xr-x?

Let’s say we’re administering a server, and a group of users wants to set up a shared directory for a new project. During the early stages of development, they only want members of the project team to be able to access and modify the data. Our server is not running a GUI, so we’ll need to know how to create a directory and modify permissions through a terminal session.

First, we’ll make a new directory for “project-a” on our server under /local:

cd /local
mkdir project-a

To check the permissions on our new directory, we can run an ls -l inside /local:

On the right-hand side, we see our directory name, “project-a.” The row contains data about our directory, which is a special type of file. From left to right, our row contains:

In the left-hand column, we see a particular string of characters:

drwxr-xr-x

The first character, “d,” tells us that we are looking at the permission set for a directory. Regular files will show a “-” instead of a “d.” (Other types do exist, but you won’t encounter them as often.)

The remaining characters tell us what permissions have been granted to each of our three categories: the first three characters (rwx in our example) correspond to Owner rights; the following three (r-x) to Group rights, and the final three (r-x) to Others rights.

An Owner with rwx permissions can do the following:

  • r – Read
    • The ability to read regular file contents or list the contents of a directory
  • w – Write
    • The ability to modify and delete regular files; within a directory, the ability to add or delete directory contents
  • x – Execute
    • The ability to run scripts or programs; in the case of directories, the ability to cd to the directory

These permissions can be combined in different ways — a Group with r-x rights to a Python script will be able to read the file contents and execute the script, but will not be able to modify or delete the file. Others with rw- access to the same script will be able to read the file contents and make changes, but not actually run the script itself.

In the case of directories, if you want someone to be able to cd to the directory and list (ls) the files it contains, you’ll want to provision r-x rights, as read permission on its own will not be sufficient. (With r-- permission to a directory, a user won’t be able to cd the directory — they need execute rights for that. Similarly, if someone were given --x rights to a directory, they would be able to cd to the directory, but would not have sufficient privilege to actually view the directory contents.)

In order for us to satisfy our goal — creating a shared directory with access restricted to members of a particular group — we’ll need to make some modifications to /local/project-a.

Assigning a Group with chgrp

First, we’ll create a group that will be assigned to the directory:

groupadd project-a

We can add members by modifying the /etc/group file manually, or using usermod like so:

usermod -aG name_of_group username

Next, we’ll assign the group to the directory:

chgrp project-a project-a

The first argument (project-a) is our group name. The second (also project-a) is our directory name. If we wanted to be more specific, we could use the full directory path*:

chgrp project-a /local/project-a

*Note: When is it necessary to use the full file/directory path?
If the file or directory you are specifying is inside the active directory (e.g. if you run “ls” and you see the file or directory listed), then you don’t need to use the full path–the file/directory name will be enough. However, if the file or directory is not inside the current directory, you will need to use the full path.

Let’s check out our directory with ls -l:

Our directory is still owned by root, but our assigned group has changed to project-a.

Next, we need to modify Group and Others permissions.

Modify Permissions with chmod

Here’s our current permission set and our target:

chmod is used to make changes:

chmod new_permission_set name_of_file_or_directory

To meet our goal, we will run:

chmod 770 /local/project-a

How does 770 correspond to rwxrwx---?

Each of the three digits in our chmod statement — 7, 7, 0 — corresponds to Owner, Group, and Others rights. Our Owner and Group are given full permissions over the directory (rwx, or 7) and all Others are given nothing (---, or 0).

Our permission set can be broken down into the following values:

Each character (r, w, x) represents a binary digit — but you don’t need to worry about binary counting. All we need to do is add up the values shown in the chart above for the permission set we want.

Here’s a table breaking down the combinations that are possible with their numerical representations. I have included binary alongside the octal (0-7) values for reference. You can see the pattern:

So, for practice, if we wanted to give a file rw-r--r-- permissions, we could run:

chmod 644 my_file_name

Back to project-a — we’ve run chmod 770, so our directory should be good to go. As a test, I have created two test accounts: testuser and testuser2. I have added testuser to the project-a group. I switch to the testuser account and try to open the project-a directory:

I switch over to the testuser2, who is not a member of the project-a group:

testuser2 receives a permission denied error when trying to open project-a — exactly the behavior we expected.

Changing Ownership with chown

Our project-a directory is complete; only members of the project-a group have access to it. The root account is still the owner, and that is fine — there is no reason for us to change the directory owner in this example.

Occasionally, we will need to change the owner of files and directories. Perhaps we are setting up a directory that only a single user should be able to access. In such a case, we could grant a group that only has one member rights to the directory, but that defies the intended use of the Group permission. The cleaner option would be to make the user the directory Owner.

In /local, we’ll build a new directory called private_directory and give it rwx------ permissions with chmod:

Currently, root is the only user with access to private_directory, because root is the Owner (and Group).

To make testuser2 the directory owner, we use chown*:

chown testuser2 private_directory

*Note: chown must be run as root. Regular users cannot run chown to change ownership on files or directories.

ls -l to view the changes:

Great! testuser2 is now the directory owner, and has become the only account with access to private_directory (root, of course, will still have access — root retains access to everything).

However, we’ve hit a bit of a snag — private_directory contains data that did not inherit the new ownership of the directory:

If we want to ensure that we’re changing the ownership on everything inside a directory, we’ll need to use the recursive flag (-R):

chown -R testuser2 private_directory

Now all of our files are owned by testuser2.

We can also use chown to set an assigned group when we are changing our Owner (owner_name:group_name):

chown -R testuser2:project-a /local/private_directory

Now our directory and its files are assigned to the group project-a. However, since private_directory does not actually grant group members any rights (---), members of the group project-a cannot access private_directory:

Using chmod Recursively

Remember that shared directory we set up for project-a? Well, some users copied some content into the directory, but not all members of the project-a group have write access to the files. They’re asking you to fix it.

We can run a chgrp recursively (by adding the -R flag) to make sure everything inside the directory is assigned to our project-a group:

chgrp -R project-a /local/project-a

However, changing the assigned group is not sufficient to ensure all group members have write access. To change the permissions on all files and subdirectories, we can use the recursive flag (-R) with chmod — but which numerical value would we use? Currently, we can see that regular files inside project-a have a permission set of rw-r--r-- or 644, and the project_data directory is set to rwxr-xr-x or 755. There may be files inside project_data with specialized permissions.

Luckily, we don’t have to decide on a uniform permission set for all files and directories — we can add group write to our existing permissions by doing the following:

chmod -R g+w /local/project-a

In this example, we have used a “g” to specify that we intend to add write privileges for our Group. But note that our options for specifying Owner, Group, and Others are a little counterintuitive when using this syntax:

Just as we added privileges with “+,” we can subtract permissions with “-,” even specifying multiple values we wish to change:

chmod -R o-rx /local/project-a

If we want to ensure that the Owner has rwx rights to all files and directories, we could run the following:

chmod -R u=rwx /local/project-a

If we wanted to grant full access to everything inside /local/project-a to everyone, we could run:

chmod -R ugo=rwx /local/project-a

Note that this is equivalent to:

chmod -R 777 /local/project-a

Here are a few more examples of chmod statements in this form:

  • chmod ug+x /path/to/file
    • Will add execute rights for Owner and Group, but will not modify other existing permissions on the file
  • chmod o-rwx /path/to/file
    • Will remove read, write, and execute rights from Others, but will not modify other existing permissions on the file
  • chmod g=rw /path/to/file
    • Will set group permissions to read-write on the file; execute rights will be removed from Group if they existed previously, and permissions for Owner and Others will remain the same

What Next?

If you’ve made it this far, congratulations — you now know the foundations of Unix file permissions!

Next time, we’ll take a deeper look at chmod and explore setuid, setgid, and the sticky bit, which give us a finer grain of control over our permissions. We’ll also look at the umask and how it affects the default permissions on new files and directories.

Farther ahead, we can take a peek at how SELinux adds another layer of complexity to our file permissions, and examine some troubleshooting scenarios in which incorrectly configured permissions cause some surprising system behavior.
